The location of the hyperintense mass in the foramen rotundum suggests involvement of the maxillary nerve, which provides sensory innervation to the cheekbone, nasolabial fold, and upper lip. Therefore, the most likely finding is decreased sensation over those areas. Option B involves the glossopharyngeal nerve, which is not related to the foramen rotundum. Option C involves the ophthalmic nerve, which exits the skull through the superior orbital fissure. Option D involves the trigeminal nerve, which exits the skull near the foramen ovale.
